Super constraints work by using EdgeQL within access policies. You can write an EdgeQL expression that defines the condition that must be met for the write operation to be considered valid. If the condition is not met, the operation is undone. Here's a simple example of an access policy that acts as a super constraint:
```
module default {
  type User {
    required property name -> str;
    property age -> int16;

    policy on insert {
      using (age >= 18)
    }
  }
}
```
In this example, the policy ensures that a `User` can only be inserted if their age is 18 or older. If someone tries to insert a `User` with an age less than 18, the insert operation will fail and be rolled back.

